[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] The term **asynchronous** refers to two or more objects or events that do not exist or happen at the same time, that is, they are **not** synchronous.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] When multiple related things happen without any being dependent on the completion of previous happenings, they are asynchronous.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] In computing, the word "asynchronous" is used in two major contexts, as explained below.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] Asynchronous communication is a method of exchanging messages in which the sending, receiving, and processing of each message is not dependent on the sending, receipt, or processing of other messages.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] In asynchronous communication, each party receives and processes messages when convenient or possible to do so, rather than doing so immediately upon receipt.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] Additionally, messages may be sent without waiting for acknowledgement, with the understanding that if a problem occurs, the recipient will request corrections or otherwise handle the situation.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] Email is a type of asynchronous human communication.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] The recipient reads the email and responds to it (or not) at their convenience, not necessarily right away.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] All parties can continue to send and receive messages at any time.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] Emails don't have to be scheduled in a particular sequence.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] In asynchronous software, making a request, such as to a server, does not block other processes while waiting for the response.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] The software can continue performing other tasks.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] For example, in promise-based APIs, `Promise` objects are created for long operations.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] After the operation is complete, the promise is handled.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] With promises, the software doesn't have to wait for the operation to finish.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] Asynchronous software design expands upon the concept by building code that allows a program to ask that a task be performed alongside the original task (or tasks), without stopping to wait for the task to complete.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] When the secondary task is completed, the original task is notified using an agreed-upon mechanism so that it knows the work is done, and that the result, if any, is available.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] There are a number of programming techniques for implementing asynchronous software.
[src:cypress-e2e/asynchronous] See the article Asynchronous JavaScript for an introduction to them.
