[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The **end-to-end** (**E2E**) **principle** is a design principle in computer networking that requires application-specific features (such as reliability and security) to be implemented in the communicating end nodes of the network, instead of in the network itself.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Intermediary nodes (such as gateways and routers) that exist to establish the network may still implement these features to improve efficiency but do not guarantee end-to-end functionality.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The essence of what would later be called the end-to-end principle was contained in the work of Donald Davies on packet-switched networks in the 1960s.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Louis Pouzin pioneered the use of the end-to-end strategy in the CYCLADES network in the 1970s.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The principle was first articulated explicitly in 1981 by Saltzer, Reed, and Clark.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The meaning of the end-to-end principle has been continuously reinterpreted ever since its initial articulation.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Noteworthy formulations of the end-to-end principle can be found before the seminal 1981 Saltzer, Reed, and Clark paper.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] A basic premise of the principle is that the payoffs from adding certain features required by the end application to the communication subsystem quickly diminish.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The end hosts have to implement these functions for correctness.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Implementing a specific function incurs some resource penalties regardless of whether the function is used or not, and implementing a specific function *in the network* adds these penalties to all clients, whether they need the function or not.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The fundamental notion behind the end-to-end principle is that for two processes communicating with each other via some communication means, the *reliability* obtained from that means cannot be expected to be perfectly aligned with the reliability requirements of the processes.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] In particular, meeting or exceeding very high-reliability requirements of communicating processes separated by networks of nontrivial size is more costly than obtaining the required degree of reliability by positive end-to-end acknowledgments and retransmissions (referred to as PAR or ARQ).
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Put differently, it is far easier to obtain reliability beyond a certain margin by mechanisms in the *end hosts* of a network rather than in the *intermediary nodes*, especially when the latter are beyond the control of, and not accountable to, the former.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Positive end-to-end acknowledgments with infinite retries can obtain arbitrarily high reliability from any network with a higher than zero probability of successfully transmitting data from one end to another.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The end-to-end principle does not extend to functions beyond end-to-end error control and correction, and security.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] E.g., no straightforward end-to-end arguments can be made for communication parameters such as latency and throughput.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The end-to-end principle is closely related, and sometimes seen as a direct precursor, to the principle of net neutrality.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] In the 1960s, Paul Baran and Donald Davies, in their pre-ARPANET elaborations of networking, made comments about reliability.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Baran introduced the concept of virtual circuits in 1962.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] His report in 1964 states: "Reliability and raw error rates are secondary.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The network must be built with the expectation of heavy damage anyway.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Davies was against the concept of virtual circuits.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Because of this, loss of packets, if it is sufficiently rare, can be tolerated." Davies built the local-area NPL network with a single packet switch and worked on the simulation of wide-area networks.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The ARPANET was the first large-scale general-purpose packet switching network – implementing several of the concepts previously articulated by Baran and Davies.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The design, led by Bob Kahn, was based on reliable virtual circuits.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The BBN "IMP Guys" developed the routing algorithm, flow control, software design, and network control.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Building on these ideas, Louis Pouzin, with Hubert Zimmermann and others, developed the CYCLADES network.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] This was the first wide-area network to implement datagrams and make the hosts responsible for the reliable delivery of data, rather than this being a centralized service of the network itself.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Concepts implemented in this network feature in TCP/IP architecture.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The ARPANET demonstrated several important aspects of the end-to-end principle.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] If the basic premise of a distributed network is packet switching, then functions such as reordering and duplicate detection inevitably have to be implemented at the logical endpoints of such a network.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] 2. a higher level concerned with various end-to-end aspects of the data transmission.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Dave Clark, one of the authors of the end-to-end principle paper, concludes: "The discovery of packets is not a consequence of the end-to-end argument.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] much like a simple I/O channel between a computer and a nearby peripheral device.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] a reality that became increasingly obvious once the ARPANET grew well beyond its initial four-node topology.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The ARPANET thus provided a strong case for the inherent limits of network-based hop-by-hop reliability mechanisms in pursuit of true end-to-end reliability.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] most importantly latency and throughput.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] the classic example being interactive real-time voice applications.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] was catered for in the ARPANET by providing a raw message service that dispensed with various reliability measures so as to provide faster and lower latency data transmission service to the end hosts.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Internet Protocol (IP) is a connectionless datagram service with no delivery guarantees.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] On the Internet, IP is used for nearly all communications.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] End-to-end acknowledgment and retransmission is the responsibility of the connection-oriented Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), which sits on top of IP.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The functional split between IP and TCP exemplifies the proper application of the end-to-end principle to transport protocol design.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] A thorough checksum is hence best done at the endpoints, and the network maintains a relatively low level of complexity and reasonable performance for all clients.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The most important limitation of the end-to-end principle is that its basic premise, placing functions in the application endpoints rather than in the intermediary nodes, is not trivial to implement.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] An example of the limitations of the end-to-end principle exists in mobile devices with mobile IPv6.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Pushing service-specific complexity to the endpoints can cause issues with mobile devices if the device has unreliable access to network channels.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Further problems can be seen with a decrease in network transparency from the addition of network address translation (NAT), which IPv4 relies on to combat address exhaustion.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] With the introduction of IPv6, users once again have unique identifiers, allowing for true end-to-end connectivity.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Unique identifiers may be based on a physical address, or can be generated randomly by the host.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The end-to-end principle advocates pushing coordination-related functionality ever higher, ultimately into the application layer.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] The premise is that application-level information enables flexible coordination between the application endpoints and yields better performance because the coordination would be exactly what is needed.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] This leads to the idea of modeling each application via its own application-specific protocol that supports the desired coordination between its endpoints while assuming only a simple lower-layer communication service.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Broadly, this idea is known as application semantics (meaning).
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Multiagent systems offer approaches based on application semantics that enable convenient implementation of distributed applications without requiring message ordering and delivery guarantees from the underlying communication services.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] A basic idea in these approaches is to model the coordination between application endpoints via an information protocol and then implement the endpoints (agents) based on the protocol.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] Information protocols can be enacted over lossy, unordered communication services.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-principle] A middleware based on information protocols and the associated programming model abstracts away message receptions from the underlying network and enables endpoint programmers to focus on the business logic for sending messages.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-testing] System testing describes testing at the system level to contrast to testing at the system integration, integration or unit level.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-testing] System testing often serves the purpose of evaluating the system's compliance with its specified requirements – often from a functional requirement specification (FRS), a system requirement specification (SRS), another type of specification or multiple.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-testing] System testing can detect defects in the system as a whole.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-testing] System testing can verify the design, the behavior and even the believed expectations of the customer.
[src:cypress-e2e/end-to-end-testing] It is also intended to test up to and beyond the bounds of specified software and hardware requirements.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress is a quality platform for teams shipping modern web applications.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We bring together end-to-end testing, component testing, accessibility checks, and a clear view of test coverage into a connected workflow that runs locally and in CI, so you can catch problems before your users do.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Most teams come to Cypress looking for a better way to write tests for their front end.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] The same platform helps a single developer write their first test, a QA team manage thousands of specs, an accessibility partner track regressions, and an engineering lead see whether a release is safe to ship.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress can test anything that runs in a browser and surface insights into how to improve the health of your test suite and the quality of your application.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] This is where the day-to-day cost of testing lives.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Most teams spend more time debugging broken tests than writing new ones, and most of that time goes to one question: what was the state of the app when the test failed?
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Less time on test maintenance is more time shipping features.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Faster, more trustworthy CI is the difference between a team that ships every day and a team that ships when they get lucky.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] If your team uses AI coding assistants, Cloud MCP gives them the same run and failure context inside your IDE.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Accessibility issues caught in development cost a few hours of engineering time.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] The same issues caught by a compliance review, a procurement gate, or a public complaint cost a great deal more.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Coverage gaps that hide in plain sight turn into the production incidents that derail your roadmap.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Below are some of the key features of each product.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress can be used to ensure several different types of tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Used together, they give you broader, more dependable coverage before release.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress was originally designed to run end-to-end (E2E) tests on anything that runs in a browser.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] A typical E2E test visits the application in a browser and performs actions via the UI just like a real user would.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] They catch the failures your users would actually see, which is what makes them so valuable in the moments before code ships.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress Component Testing mounts your components directly in a real browser, giving you a live, visual workbench to build and test components from any front-end UI library — no matter how simple or complex.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Because tests run in the same environment your users experience, you catch rendering issues, interaction bugs, and edge cases before they ever reach end-to-end testing or production.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Learn more about how to test components for React, Angular, Vue, and Svelte.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] You can write Cypress tests to check the accessibility of your application, and use plugins to run broad accessibility scans.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] When combined with Cypress Accessibility in Cypress Cloud, insights can be surfaced when specific accessibility standards are not met through your testing, with no configuration required.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] See our Accessibility Testing guide for more details.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] You can increase release confidence by closing testing gaps in critical app flows using UI Coverage.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Use data-driven insights to cover untested areas, reduce incidents, and improve app quality across the team.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress can perform arbitrary HTTP calls, thus you can use it for API testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] And through a large number of official and 3rd party plugins you can write many other types of tests!
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Our mission is to build a thriving testing solution that enhances productivity, makes testing an enjoyable experience, and generates developer happiness.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We hold ourselves accountable to champion a testing process **that actually works**.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We believe our documentation should be approachable.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] This means enabling our readers to understand fully not just the **what** but the **why** as well.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We want to help developers build a new generation of modern applications faster, better, and without the stress and anxiety associated with managing tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We aim to elevate the art of software development by leveraging test results to generate actionable insights for long-term stability by proactively identifying areas for improvement.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We know that in order for us to be successful we must enable, nurture, and foster an ecosystem that thrives on open source.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Every line of test code is an investment in **your codebase**, it will never be coupled to us as a paid service or company.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Tests will be able to run and work independently, *always*.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We believe testing needs a lot of ❤️ and we are here to build a tool, a service, and a community that everyone can learn and benefit from.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We're solving the hardest pain points shared by every developer working on the web.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] We believe in this mission and hope that you will join us to make Cypress a lasting ecosystem that makes everyone happy.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Most testing tools (like Selenium) operate by running outside of the browser and executing remote commands across the network.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] *Cypress is the exact opposite.* Cypress is executed in the same run loop as your application.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Behind Cypress is a Node server process.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress and the Node process constantly communicate, synchronize, and perform tasks on behalf of each other.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Having access to both parts (front and back) gives us the ability to respond to your application's events in real time, while at the same time work outside of the browser for tasks that require a higher privilege.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress ultimately controls the entire automation process from top to bottom, which puts it in the unique position of being able to understand everything happening in and outside of the browser.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] This means Cypress is capable of delivering more consistent results than any other testing tool.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Because Cypress is installed locally on your machine, it can additionally tap into the operating system for automation tasks.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] This makes performing tasks such as taking screenshots, recording videos, general file system operations and network operations possible.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Because Cypress operates within your application, that means it has native access to every single object.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Whether it is the `window`, the `document`, a DOM element, your application instance, a function, a timer, a service worker, or anything else - you have access to it in your Cypress tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress allows for browser context to be cached with `cy.session()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] This means as a user, you only need to perform authentication once for the entirety of your test suite, and restore the saved session between each test.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] That means you do not have to visit a login page, type in a username and password and wait for the page to load and/or redirect for every test you run.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] You can accomplish this once with `cy.session()` and if needed, `cy.origin()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Flake is one of the largest hidden costs in any test suite.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Reducing it is one of the most direct ways Cypress keeps a suite trustworthy over time.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress knows and understands everything that happens in your application synchronously.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] It is notified the moment the page loads and the moment the page unloads.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress even knows how fast an element is animating and will wait for it to stop animating.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Additionally, it automatically waits for elements to become visible, to become enabled, and to stop being covered.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] When pages begin to transition, Cypress will pause command execution until the following page is fully loaded.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] You can also tell Cypress to wait on specific network requests to finish.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Above all else Cypress is built for usability.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] While there are many new and powerful capabilities of Cypress - there are also important trade-offs that we've made in making this possible.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] If you're interested in understanding more, we've written an entire guide on this topic.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Install Cypress so you can quickly see your first passing test within minutes for End-to-end tests or Component tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Cypress makes it quick and easy to start testing, and as you begin to test your app, **you'll often wonder if you're using best practices or scalable strategies**.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] The RWA achieves full code-coverage with end-to-end tests across multiple browsers and device sizes, but also includes visual regression tests, API tests, unit tests, and runs them all in an efficient CI pipeline.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] Use the RWA to **learn, experiment, tinker, and practice** web application testing with Cypress.
[src:cypress-e2e/get-started-why-cypress] The app is bundled with everything you need, just clone the repository and start testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress commands don't do anything at the moment they are invoked, but rather enqueue themselves to be run later.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Commands can be chained together because Cypress manages a Promise chain on your behalf, with each command yielding a 'subject' to the next command, until the chain ends or an error is encountered.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Learn more about how commands chain together in the Introduction to Chains of Commands.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] The differences between queries and other commands are outline in the Retry-ability Guide.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Queries are Cypress commands that read the state of your application.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] They return a subject for further commands to act or assert on, and retry as needed to make sure the DOM element or other data they yield is always up to date.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Assertions are Cypress commands that assert on the state of your application.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] They pause your test until the given condition is met, or until they time out.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Learn more about Cypress assertions in the Introduction to Assertions and the Assertions Reference.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Actions are Cypress commands that interact with your application as a user would.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] They wait for elements to be actionable before interacting with the page.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Learn more about action commands in our Actionability Guide.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress has a variety of additional commands to help write tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress emits a series of events as it runs in your browser.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] These events are useful not only to control your application's behavior, but also for debugging purposes.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Learn more about them in the Catalog of Events.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress exposes interfaces to write Custom Commands and Custom Queries.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Command Plugins which you can install or download.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress exposes a number of properties and methods on the global `Cypress` object.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] The *key* difference between Cypress APIs and Cypress commands is that Cypress APIs execute the moment they are invoked and are **not** enqueued to run at a later time.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] Cypress makes several common libraries available directly on the global `Cypress` object.
[src:cypress-e2e/table-of-contents] The Node Events allow you to hook into and extend Cypress behavior.
