[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:cypress-e2e/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] A web application performance tool (WAPT) is used to test web applications and web related interfaces.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] These tools are used for performance, load and stress testing of web applications, web sites, web API, web servers and other web interfaces.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] WAPT tends to simulate virtual users which will repeat either recorded URLs or specified URL and allows the users to specify number of times or iterations that the virtual users will have to repeat the recorded URLs.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] By doing so, the tool is useful to check for bottleneck and performance leakage in the website or web application being tested.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] WAPT allows a user to specify how virtual users are involved in the testing environment.ie either increasing users or constant users or periodic users load.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] Increasing user load, step by step is called RAMP where virtual users are increased from 0 to hundreds.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] Constant user load maintains specified user load at all time.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] Periodic user load tends to increase and decrease the user load from time to time.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] Web security testing tells us whether Web-based applications requirements are met when they are subjected to malicious input data.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] An application programming interface API exposes services to other software components, which can query the API.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] The API implementation is in charge of computing the service and returning the result to the component that send the query.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] A part of web testing focuses on testing these web API implementations.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] GraphQL is a specific query and API language.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] It is the focus of tailored testing techniques.
[src:cypress-e2e/web-testing] Search-based test generation yields good results to generate test cases for GraphQL APIs.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress favors **convention over configuration**.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] When you add a new project, Cypress scaffolds a suggested folder structure so you can start writing tests immediately, without deciding where everything should live or wiring up a build step.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Everything below can be reconfigured, but the defaults are designed to get out of your way.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] These locations are conventions, not requirements.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can point Cypress at different folders for your tests, fixtures, and support files, which is useful when you're fitting Cypress into an existing repository layout.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If you're starting your first project, we recommend sticking with the defaults above so your setup matches our docs and examples.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can change these paths in your configuration file.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] See the Cypress configuration reference for the full list of options.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] What files should I add to my '.gitignore file' ?
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress may create asset files in a `downloadsFolder`, a `screenshotsFolder` or a `videosFolder` to store any downloads, screenshots or videos created during the testing of your application.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Because these are generated artifacts rather than source, many users add these folders to their .gitignore file (see below for an example).
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Additionally, if you are storing sensitive variables in your Cypress configuration these should also be ignored when you check into source control.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] For end-to-end testing they're located in `cypress/e2e` by default, while component testing specs typically live next to the components they test anywhere in your project.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Either way, you can configure a different location.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress also supports `ES2015` out of the box.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can use either `ES2015 modules` or `CommonJS modules`, which means you can `import` or `require` both **npm packages** and **local relative modules** to share code across specs.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Check out our recipe using ES2015 and CommonJS modules.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress doesn't treat every file in your test folder as a spec.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] This convention lets you keep helper files and specs side by side without Cypress trying to run your helpers as tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The trade-off is that a file named `cypress/e2e/login.js` is **not** discovered, while `cypress/e2e/login.cy.js` is.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If a test you've written isn't showing up, the filename almost always doesn't match `specPattern`, so that's the first thing to check.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can override `specPattern` in your configuration if you prefer a different naming convention.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] `specPattern` defines the full set of files Cypress *considers* to be specs.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] In short: `specPattern` is the master list, `excludeSpecPattern` subtracts from it, and `--spec` picks which of the remaining specs to run this time.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The support file is your hook into every spec.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] It runs **before** every single spec file, which makes it the natural home for setup and behavior you want available everywhere, without importing it into each spec yourself.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] That's why it's the recommended place for custom commands and global overrides.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To control what loads first, set the `supportFile` path.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] When Cypress runs a spec file via `cypress open` or `cypress run`, it loads the support file first and then the spec file.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] `supportFile` is configured separately for each testing type.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Set it under the `e2e` key for end-to-end testing and under the `component` key for component testing in your Cypress configuration.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] From your support file you can `import` or `require` other files to keep things organized as it grows.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress bundles the support file and everything it imports, then loads that bundle **before every single spec file**, so the cost of anything you import there is paid on every spec run.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Avoid importing large modules or anything that isn't needed for testing (especially Node.js-only code like database drivers or `fs`, which can't run in the browser).
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Import heavy or spec-specific code directly in the spec files that need it instead.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] See Keep support and spec imports lean in the test performance guide for examples.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Fixtures are external pieces of static data your tests can load on demand.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Think of them as the canned data your tests run against.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Keeping this data in its own file (rather than inline in the test) makes specs easier to read and lets you reuse the same data across many tests.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Fixture files live in `cypress/fixtures` by default, but can be configured to another directory.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress recognizes a range of fixture file types and parses or encodes each based on its extension: `.json`, `.js`, `.coffee`, `.html`, `.txt`, `.csv`, `.png`, `.jpg`, `.jpeg`, `.gif`, `.tif`, `.tiff`, and `.zip`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Any other extension is read as `utf8` unless you pass a different encoding.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] See `cy.fixture()` for the full encoding details.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Your tests run in the browser, but some things, like touching the file system, talking to a database, or controlling how specs are bundled, can only happen in Node.js.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress lets you run that Node.js-side code through the `setupNodeEvents` function in your Cypress configuration, defined per testing type under the `e2e` or `component` options.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] It runs in the background Node.js process before the project is loaded, before the browser launches, and during your test run, and your tests reach it through the cy.task() command.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] This is where you tap into Node events to do things like control how spec files are bundled with preprocessors, find and launch browsers via the browser launch API, and run other tasks that need access to the operating system.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Read our plugins guide for details and examples.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] When a run produces artifacts (files your app downloaded, screenshots, or videos), Cypress saves them to dedicated folders so you can inspect what happened after the fact.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Because these are regenerated on every run, you'll usually want to keep them out of source control.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Any files downloaded while testing an application's file download feature will be stored in the `downloadsFolder` which is set to `cypress/downloads` by default.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If screenshots were taken via the cy.screenshot() command or automatically when a test fails, the screenshots are stored in the `screenshotsFolder` which is set to `cypress/screenshots` by default.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Any videos recorded of the run are stored in the `videosFolder` which is set to `cypress/videos` by default.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Screenshots and videos are saved inside their respective folders (`cypress/screenshots`, `cypress/videos`), and Cypress mirrors each spec's folder structure underneath so every asset lines up with the spec that produced it.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To keep those paths from getting needlessly deep, Cypress first removes the **common ancestor**: the longest folder path shared by *every* spec in the run (the specs matched by `specPattern`, or by the `--spec` flag / `spec` Module API option when you've narrowed the run).
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Only the part of each spec's path that is unique is kept.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] One consequence is that the same spec can produce assets at different paths depending on which other specs ran alongside it, because adding or removing specs can change the shared ancestor.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The examples below show how the kept portion of the path changes with the set of specs in the run: first a single end-to-end spec, then two colocated component specs.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Component specs usually sit right next to the components they test.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If you still need the folder layout itself to be consistent, keep all your specs under a single common directory so the common ancestor doesn't shift as you add, remove, or filter specs.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Managing these artifacts by hand gets tedious as a suite grows.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Instead of administering assets yourself, you can save them to the cloud with Cypress Cloud.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Replay the test as it executed during the recorded run with full debug capability using (Replay Icon) Cypress Test Replay.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Screenshots and videos are attached to their respective test results and kept for the length of your data retention period, and are easily shared or browsed through our web interface.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To learn more about videos and settings available, see Screenshots and Videos.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress is built on top of Mocha and Chai, two libraries the JavaScript community has relied on for years.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Building on them rather than inventing a new test language means the syntax is already familiar and battle-tested: Cypress supports both Chai's `BDD` and `TDD` assertion styles, and your tests will mostly follow those conventions.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress Studio generates test commands for you as you click and type in your app, so you can build up a spec without writing it by hand.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Connect Cypress Cloud to also unlock **Studio AI**, which suggests assertions for you while you record.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The test interface, borrowed from Mocha, provides `describe()`, `context()`, `it()` and `specify()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You use `describe()`/`context()` to group related tests and `it()`/`specify()` to define an individual test, which keeps your specs readable and your test output organized.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] `context()` is identical to `describe()` and `specify()` is identical to `it()`, so choose whatever terminology works best for you.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress supports both BDD (`expect`/`should`) and TDD (`assert`) style plain assertions, so you can write assertions in whichever style your team prefers.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The .should() command and its alias .and() can also be used to more easily chain assertions off of Cypress commands.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Hooks (also borrowed from Mocha) let you run setup and teardown code around your tests instead of repeating it inside each one.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Use them to establish the conditions a group of tests needs before they run, or to tidy up afterward.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] 🚨 Before writing `after()` or `afterEach()` hooks, please see our thoughts on the anti-pattern of cleaning up state with `after()` or `afterEach()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] While developing, you rarely want to run the entire suite on every save.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress lets you focus on or skip specific tests so your feedback loop stays fast.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To run a specified suite or test, append `.only` to the function.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] All nested suites will also be executed.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] This gives you the ability to run one test at a time and is the recommended way to write a test suite.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To skip a specified suite or test, append `.skip()` to the function.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Tests that quietly depend on each other are a leading cause of flaky suites: a test passes only because an earlier test left the browser in a particular state, and the moment you reorder, skip, or run them in isolation, things break.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] As stated in our mission, we hold ourselves accountable to champion a testing process that actually works, and have built Cypress to guide developers toward writing independent tests from the start.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] We do this by cleaning up test state and the browser context *before* each test so the actions of one test can't affect another.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The goal for each test is to **reliably pass** whether it runs in isolation or alongside others, which removes a whole category of nondeterministic failures that are painful to debug.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The behavior of running tests in a clean browser context is called `testIsolation`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Test isolation is **enabled by default** (`testIsolation: true`) and applies only to end-to-end testing.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] It is a global configuration and can be overridden for end-to-end testing at the `describe` level with the `testIsolation` option.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] To learn more about this behavior and the trade-offs of disabling it, review our Test Isolation guide.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Sometimes a test or suite needs different settings than the rest of your project, such as a specific viewport, a particular browser, or a different retry count.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Rather than changing global configuration, you can apply test configuration locally by passing a configuration object as the second argument to the test or suite function.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] These values take effect only for the suite or tests where they're set, then revert to their previous defaults once those tests complete, so the override stays scoped and doesn't leak into the rest of your run.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If you want to target a suite of tests to run or be excluded when run in a specific browser, you can override the `browser` configuration within the suite configuration.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The `browser` option accepts the same arguments as Cypress.isBrowser().
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The following suite of tests will be skipped if running tests in Chrome browsers.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The following suite of tests will only execute when running in the Firefox browser.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Additionally, it will overwrite the viewport resolution.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can configure the number of retry attempts during `cypress run` or `cypress open`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can also pass an `expose` object so plugins can declare public configuration per suite or test, readable with `Cypress.expose()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Use this only for non-sensitive values, since exposed configuration is accessible in the browser context.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Because tests are just JavaScript, you can generate them programmatically.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] This keeps your specs DRY when you need to run the same assertions across a list of inputs: change the data and the tests follow, with no copy-paste.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] A common use of dynamic tests is **data-driven testing**: keeping your test cases (and often their titles) in an external data source, then generating one test per row.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The important constraint is that the `describe()`/`it()` structure is built **synchronously when the spec loads**.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress commands like `cy.fixture()` and `cy.task()` run *inside* a test and resolve asynchronously, so they can supply data **within** a test but cannot be used to create the `it()` blocks themselves.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The data has to be available at load time.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Each `it()` title comes straight from the data, so the row's `title` is what shows up in your test output.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] For formats that need parsing in Node.js first, such as **CSV or Excel**, read and parse the file inside `setupNodeEvents` and hand the parsed rows to the browser with the `expose` configuration, then read them in your spec with `Cypress.expose()`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Use `expose` only for non-sensitive data, since exposed values are accessible in the browser context.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] You can run a test by clicking on the spec filename.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] For example the Cypress RealWorld App has multiple test files, but below we run the "new-transaction.spec.ts" test file by clicking on it.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] A big part of why Cypress feels productive is the tight feedback loop.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] When you run with cypress open, Cypress watches the filesystem for changes to your spec files.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Soon after you add or update a test, Cypress reloads it and re-runs every test in that spec file, so you can write tests as you build a feature and the UI always reflects your latest edits, with no manual re-run.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress watches your entire project root for spec files.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Any file that matches your `specPattern`, wherever it lives in the project, is detected.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] When a change is made, the active spec file, the support file, and any files they `import` (or `require`) are recompiled through the preprocessor and the browser reloads.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Your application code is intentionally left out: if you're developing with a modern JS-based stack, you likely already have some form of hot module replacement watching your application code (HTML, CSS, JS, etc.) and reloading it in response to changes, so Cypress doesn't duplicate that work.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] **Nothing** is watched during cypress run, so the `watchForFileChanges` property has no effect there.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The component responsible for the file-watching behavior in Cypress is the `@cypress/webpack-batteries-included-preprocessor`.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] This is the default preprocessor packaged with Cypress and is registered automatically when you don't provide your own `file:preprocessor` event.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] It builds on the lower-level `webpack-preprocessor` and bundles the loaders and configuration needed to give you TypeScript and JSX support out of the box with zero configuration.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] That zero-config support is the reason most projects never have to think about bundling at all.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] If you need further control of the file-watching behavior you can configure this preprocessor explicitly: it exposes options that allow you to configure behavior such as *what* is watched and the delay before emitting an "update" event after a change.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Cypress also ships other file-watching preprocessors - you'll have to configure these explicitly if you want to use them.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Once a spec finishes, knowing how to read its results is what turns a run into actionable feedback.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Every test ends in one of four statuses: **passed**, **failed**, **pending**, or **skipped**.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] These statuses are inherited from Mocha, the test runner Cypress is built on.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Passed tests have successfully completed all their hooks and commands without failing any assertions.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Note that a test can pass after several test retries.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] In that case the Command Log shows some failed attempts, but ultimately the entire test finishes successfully.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] A failed hook or test means an assertion didn't pass or a command errored.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] That's the test doing its job: catching the problem in your suite before it reaches a user.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] After a test fails, the Test Replay or screenshots and videos with Cypress Cloud can help find the problem so it can be fixed.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] A **pending** test is one that Cypress intentionally doesn't run because you told it not to.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] In each case you've knowingly told Cypress to hold off, so it reports the test as pending rather than passed or failed.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Unlike a pending test, which you deliberately leave out, a **skipped** test is one Cypress *meant* to run but couldn't because a shared hook failed.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Imagine a block of tests that all share a `beforeEach` hook, and that hook errors.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] The hook fails before the first test can run, so that test is marked **failed**.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] Because the same hook would fail identically for every other test in the block, Cypress doesn't re-run it; it marks the remaining tests as **skipped** instead.
[src:cypress-e2e/writing-and-organizing-tests] In short, a test is skipped when a `before`, `beforeEach`, or `afterEach` hook fails and prevents the tests that depend on it from running.
